Relationships

In the last exercise you learned about between and within variation. In this exercise we explore measures of dispersion or variation for one variable (variance and standard deviation) or two variables (covariance). In this way we build the basics of correlational analysis from scratch.

The latin prefix co- (or con-) indicates that one variable varies with another variable.

Standard Deviation Formula

The standard deviation is the square root of the average squared deviation from the mean, i.e.Â the square root of the variance. What is so standard about it? The scale is the same as the unit as measurement. A low standard deviation indicates that the data points tend to be very close the mean; a high standard deviation indicates that the data points are spread out over a large range of values.

sqrt(var(x))
## [1] 9.899495
sd(x)
## [1] 9.899495

Covariance Formula (1 pt)

Covariance is a measure of the joint variability of two variables. The main idea of covariance is to classify three types of relationships: positive, negative or no relationship. For each data point, we multiply the differences with the respective mean. When both values are smaller or greater than the mean, the result will be positive.

# Covariance Calculation by Command
cov(x,y)
## [1] 117.5

Please look up the covariance formula and implement it in R.

Think of covariance this way: The two means of x and y constitute a new coordinate system. Data points that fall into quadrant I and III (upper right and lower left) are classified as positive and points in quadrant II or IV as negative.

Figure 1: What is the difference between covariance and correlation?

Correlation (2 pt)

Covariance quantifies a relationship and is similar to correlation but when the covariance is calculated, the data are not standardized. Therefore, the covariance is expressed in units that vary with the data and is not converted to a standardized scale of 1 to +1. Because the data are not standardized, you cannot use the covariance statistic to assess the strength of a linear relationship (a covariance of 117 can be very low for one relationship and 0.23 very high for another relationship). To assess the strength of a relationship between two variables use a correlation coefficient.

# Basic function
cor(x,y)
## [1] 0.9564548
# More advanced function (correlation + hypothesis test)
cor.test(x,y)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  x and y
## t = 5.6757, df = 3, p-value = 0.01084
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4751038 0.9972195
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.9564548

The correlation coefficient is the preferred way to describe a linear relationship.

Notice that the correlation test also is based on a t-value (t = 5.6757) and returns a p-value (0.0108) for statistical significance. Please look up the exact formula to produce this t- and p-value and implement it in R.

Correlation and Regression (1)

Linear regression is the major tool in social science. When you have a simple regression (Y and X) itâs almost identical to a correlational analysis. So whatâs the difference between correlation and simple regression?

linear_model <- lm(Total.Semesters~Age, data=GF_less_99)
linear_model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Total.Semesters ~ Age, data = GF_less_99)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)          Age  
##     -0.9898       0.3559

The regression coefficient of age is 0.6391. What is the Pearson correlation coefficient (between -1 and 1)?

GF_cor <- cor(GF_less_99$Age, GF_less_99$Total.Semesters, method="pearson")

The correlation coefficient and regression coefficient are related:

  • Both quantify the direction and strength of the relationship between two numeric variables.
  • When the correlation (r) is negative, the regression slope (b) will be negative.

They only coincide when the two variables are on the same scale, in some sense. The most common way of achieving this is through standardization.

\[\beta = cor(Y,X) \cdot \frac{SD(Y)}{SD(X)} \]

Please implement the above formula for the given GF data, i.e.Â please show the equivalence of the beta coefficient GF_beta and the correlation coefficient GF_cor after standardization with standard deviations. If this returns FALSE, think about why (inspect the returns) and find a solution.

Centering and Standardization

In regression, it is sometimes/often recommended to center the variables so that the predictors have mean 0. This makes it easier to interpret the intercept term as the expected value of \(Y\) when the predictor values are set to their means. Otherwise, the intercept is interpreted as the expected value of \(Y\) when the predictors are set to 0, which may not be a realistic or interpretable situation (e.g.Â what if the predictors were height and weight?). Note:In many models, youâre not really interested in the intercept.

GF_scaled <- GF_less_99
GF_scaled$Age <- scale(GF_scaled$Age, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE) 
GF_scaled$Total.Semesters <- scale(GF_scaled$Total.Semesters, center = TRUE, scale = TRUE) 

linear_model_scaled <- lm(Total.Semesters ~ Age, data=GF_scaled)

Centering describes subtracting the mean (or another constant) from a variable. What it does is redefine the 0 point for that predictor to be whatever value you subtracted. Standardization goes one step further by dividing by the standard deviation. The results will be data with mean = 0 and sd = 1.

Standardization changes the axes. The data cloud and regression line are identical. The correlation coefficient for these data sets are identical. If you compare the correlation coefficient and regression coefficient of the scaled data and scaled model, they are identical by design (without any further modification).

# Correlation is identical
round(cor(GF_less_99$Age, GF_less_99$Total.Semesters),10) == round(cor(GF_scaled$Age, GF_scaled$Total.Semesters),10)
##      [,1]
## [1,] TRUE
